<section xml:id="sec_circularHM" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Relationship to Circular Motion</title>
			
<p>
Consider a particle in uniform circular motion with angular velocity <m> \omega(t) </m>. The <m>x</m>-component of the particle's position when the particle has angular position <m> \theta(t)</m> and radius <m> r=A </m> can be written using trigonometric relations as

<me> x = A\cos(\phi) </me>

This is equivalent to the position function <m> x(t) = A \cos(\omega_s t + \phi_o) </m> for an oscillating block on a spring with initial condition <m> \phi_o = 0 </m>  at <m> t=0 </m>. Recall the angular velocity is the rate of change of angular position

<me> \omega(t) = \frac{d\theta}{dt} </me> 

This equation is separable. A small change in angle can be written, 

<me> d\theta = \omega(t) dt </me>

If the particle is in uniform circular motion, then <m> \omega(t) = \omega </m> is constant in time. Integrating both sides of the relationship

<me> \int_{\theta_o}^{\theta} d \theta = \omega \int_{0}^{t} dt \rightarrow \theta(t) = \omega t + \theta_o </me>

As time increases, the particle's <m>x</m>-component can be written as

<me> x(t) = A \cos(\theta(t) = A \cos(\omega t + \theta_o) </me>

As the particle moves in a circle, its projection onto the <m>x</m>-axis oscillates between <m> x = \pm A </m>. Thus, <alert> uniform circular motion is simple harmonic motion when projected onto one spatial axis </alert>. 
</p>

