<p>
This can also help you understand the meaning of the <alert> initial phase </alert>. The <alert> phase </alert> in oscillatory motion is given by <m> \phi = \omega_s t +\phi_o</m> and is analogous to the angle of a particle in circular motion <m> \theta = \omega t +\theta_o</m>. The initial phase <m>\phi_o </m> in oscillatory motion is analogous to the initial angle <m>\theta_o</m> when <m> t = 0 </m>. Setting <m> t = 0 </m> in the position function for a simple harmonic oscillator, you can find the initial <m>x</m>-position

<me> x_0 = A \cos(\theta_o) </me> 

Thus different values of the phase constant represent different starting points on the circle and correspond to different <em> initial conditions </em> of the motion. 
</p>

